<!-- ========== SECTION 1 ========== -->\
<h2 id="s1"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56620 </span> 1. What USB/IP Is \'97 Full Technical Origin Story</h2>\
\
<div class="sec-intro">\
USB/IP is an open-source software system that transparently tunnels USB device communications (at the URB level, below all drivers) over standard TCP/IP networks. It was born from academic research, merged into the Linux kernel in 2014, and has since spawned an ecosystem of implementations, GUIs, and commercial products across every major platform.\
</div>\
\
<h3>Origins</h3>\
<p>USB/IP was created by <strong>Takahiro Hirofuchi</strong> and colleagues at the National Institute of Information and Communications Technology (NICT) in Japan. It was first published in a paper titled <em>"A Portable USB Device Driver for Distributed Systems"</em> at the USENIX Annual Technical Conference 2005 (FREENIX track) and won the <strong>FREENIX Best Paper Award</strong>.</p>\
\
<p>The project was hosted on SourceForge at <code>usbip.sourceforge.net</code> and gradually gained adoption. The Linux kernel developers began incorporating it into the staging tree (as an out-of-tree module) starting in 2009. It was officially promoted to the mainline Linux kernel at <strong>version 3.17 in 2014</strong>, where it remains as a first-class kernel subsystem maintained by the kernel community.</p>\
\
<div class="card ca">\
  <h4>The Core Insight of the Original Paper</h4>\
  <p>The designers observed that USB devices are fundamentally "request/response" \'97 an OS submits a USB Request Block (URB), and the device responds. If you can serialize that request and response and transport them over any reliable byte stream (TCP), you can make a device on Machine A appear locally attached to Machine B with zero changes to drivers, firmware, or applications. The USB stack on the client machine is completely unaware anything is remote.</p>\
</div>\
\
<h3>Key Properties</h3>\
<ul>\
  <li><strong>Not a USB standard</strong> \'97 USB/IP is open-source software, not an official USB-IF specification. There is no hardware "USB/IP" port.</li>\
  <li><strong>Operates below all drivers</strong> \'97 The stub driver intercepts URBs before they reach the normal device driver on the server side.</li>\
  <li><strong>Applications see nothing different</strong> \'97 An application running on the client machine uses the remote device exactly as if it were locally attached.</li>\
  <li><strong>Protocol documented in kernel</strong> \'97 See <code>Documentation/usb/usbip_protocol.rst</code> in the Linux kernel tree.</li>\
  <li><strong>Default TCP port: 3240</strong></li>\
  <li><strong>No native authentication or encryption</strong> \'97 raw plaintext protocol (more on this in Section 21).</li>\
</ul>\
\
<!-- ========== SECTION 2 ========== -->\
<h2 id="s2"><span class="ico">\uc0\u9881 \u65039 </span> 2. How the Protocol Works \'97 Kernel Modules, URBs, TCP Framing</h2>\
\
<h3>The Five Kernel Components</h3>\
<table>\
  <tr><th>Module</th><th>Side</th><th>Function</th><th>Load command</th></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>usbip_core</code></td><td>Both</td><td>Shared utilities, protocol definitions, URB serialization</td><td>Auto (dep of others)</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>usbip_host</code></td><td>Server</td><td>Stub driver \'97 binds to physical device, intercepts all URBs, sends them over TCP</td><td><code>modprobe usbip_host</code></td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>vhci_hcd</code></td><td>Client</td><td>Virtual HCI driver \'97 creates fake USB bus, receives URBs over TCP, presents device to OS</td><td><code>modprobe vhci-hcd</code></td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>usbip_vudc</code></td><td>Device emulation</td><td>USB/IP Virtual USB Device Controller \'97 allows a Linux machine to <em>emulate</em> a USB device (advanced, rarely used)</td><td><code>modprobe usbip_vudc</code></td></tr>\
</table>\
\
<h3>The TCP Connection Lifecycle</h3>\
<p>The client opens a TCP/IP connection to the server and sends an <code>OP_REQ_IMPORT</code> packet. The server replies with <code>OP_REP_IMPORT</code>. If the import was successful, the TCP/IP connection remains open and is used to transfer URB traffic between client and server. The client may send two types of packets: <code>USBIP_CMD_SUBMIT</code> to submit a URB, and <code>USBIP_CMD_UNLINK</code> to unlink a previously submitted URB. The server's answers are <code>USBIP_RET_SUBMIT</code> and <code>USBIP_RET_UNLINK</code> respectively.</p>\
\
<h3>Two-Phase Protocol</h3>\
<div class="g2">\
  <div class="card">\
    <h4>Phase 1: Device Discovery</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>Client sends <code>OP_REQ_DEVLIST</code> to enumerate all exported devices</li>\
      <li>Server responds with <code>OP_REP_DEVLIST</code> containing device descriptors</li>\
      <li>Client chooses a device and sends <code>OP_REQ_IMPORT</code></li>\
      <li>Server responds with <code>OP_REP_IMPORT</code> \'97 connection is now "attached"</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card">\
    <h4>Phase 2: URB Transfer (ongoing)</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>Every USB I/O becomes a <code>USBIP_CMD_SUBMIT</code></li>\
      <li>Server executes the URB against the physical device</li>\
      <li>Response comes back as <code>USBIP_RET_SUBMIT</code></li>\
      <li>Connection is full-duplex \'97 multiple URBs can be in flight simultaneously (pipelined by sequence number)</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
</div>\
\
<h3>The Userspace Daemon</h3>\
<p>The <code>usbipd</code> daemon (part of the <code>usbutils</code> or <code>usbip</code> package on Linux) manages the lifecycle: starting the TCP listener, accepting connections, and coordinating with the kernel modules. On Windows, <code>usbipd-win</code> (dorssel) installs as a Windows Service that handles the same role.</p>\
\
<!-- ========== SECTION 3 ========== -->\
<h2 id="s3"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56545 </span> 3. The 4 USB Transfer Types \'97 Why They Matter for USB/IP</h2>\
\
<div class="sec-intro">\
Every USB communication uses one of four transfer types. Understanding these is the key to predicting whether a device will work reliably over USB/IP \'97 and why webcams are so much harder than hard drives.\
</div>\
\
<table>\
  <tr>\
    <th>Type</th>\
    <th>Bandwidth guarantee</th>\
    <th>Delivery guarantee</th>\
    <th>Latency</th>\
    <th>Max size / frame</th>\
    <th>Used for</th>\
    <th>USB/IP reliability</th>\
  </tr>\
  <tr>\
    <td><strong>Control</strong></td>\
    <td>Reserved (10%)</td>\
    <td>Yes (retry)</td>\
    <td>Low</td>\
    <td>64 bytes (FS) / 512 (HS)</td>\
    <td>Device enumeration, configuration, class commands</td>\
    <td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td>\
  </tr>\
  <tr>\
    <td><strong>Bulk</strong></td>\
    <td>None (uses spare)</td>\
    <td>Yes (retry)</td>\
    <td>Variable</td>\
    <td>512 bytes (HS) / 1024 (SS)</td>\
    <td>Storage, printers, most peripherals</td>\
    <td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td>\
  </tr>\
  <tr>\
    <td><strong>Interrupt</strong></td>\
    <td>Polling interval (1\'96255ms)</td>\
    <td>Yes (retry)</td>\
    <td>Guaranteed &lt;=interval</td>\
    <td>64 bytes (FS) / 1024 (HS)</td>\
    <td>HID: keyboard, mouse, gamepad, joystick</td>\
    <td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Good</span></td>\
  </tr>\
  <tr>\
    <td><strong>Isochronous</strong></td>\
    <td>Yes \'97 guaranteed bandwidth reservation</td>\
    <td><strong>No</strong> \'97 drops silently</td>\
    <td>Fixed period (1ms frames)</td>\
    <td>1023 bytes (FS) / 3072 (HS)</td>\
    <td>Webcams, audio, video capture, MIDI</td>\
    <td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Problematic</span></td>\
  </tr>\
</table>\
\
<div class="warn-box">\
  <strong>\uc0\u9888 \u65039  The Fundamental Isochronous Problem:</strong> Isochronous transfers have guaranteed bandwidth but <em>no delivery guarantee</em> \'97 they are designed to drop packets rather than retransmit late data, because stale audio/video frames are useless. TCP, however, retransmits everything and adds variable latency (jitter). When you try to tunnel isochronous data over TCP, you get the worst of both: the timing requirements of isochronous with the variable latency of TCP. Any network jitter causes the VHCI to miss isochronous scheduling windows, producing corrupted streams, dropped frames, error messages in <code>dmesg</code>, or full device disconnection.\
</div>\
\
<!-- ========== SECTION 4 ========== -->\
<h2 id="s4"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56580 </span> 4. Server vs Client \'97 Why the Naming is Backwards</h2>\
\
<div class="warn-box">\
  "Client" and "server" are confusing. A server host has physical USB devices which are exported to a client host. In the server host, load <code>usbip_common_mod.ko</code> and <code>vhci-hcd.ko</code>, and then use <code>usbipd</code>. The client host imports a USB device virtually; the client host may not have a real USB device. In the client host, load <code>usbip_common_mod.ko</code> and <code>usbip.ko</code>, and then use <code>usbip</code>.\
</div>\
\
<div class="g2">\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55357 \u56741 \u65039  USB/IP SERVER = has the physical USB device</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>Runs <code>usbipd</code> daemon, listens on TCP 3240</li>\
      <li>"Exports" devices to the network</li>\
      <li>Loads <code>usbip_host</code> module</li>\
      <li>Binds to USB device with <code>usbip bind</code></li>\
      <li>Counter-intuitive: the machine with the hardware is the "server"</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55357 \u56507  USB/IP CLIENT = wants to use the remote device</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>Runs <code>usbip attach</code> to connect to a server</li>\
      <li>"Imports" a remote device, which appears locally</li>\
      <li>Loads <code>vhci-hcd</code> module</li>\
      <li>Applications on the client see a normal local USB device</li>\
      <li>Can be both simultaneously \'97 export some devices while importing others</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
</div>\
\
<!-- ========== SECTION 5 ========== -->\
<h2 id="s5"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56550 </span> 5. USB/IP Protocol Wire Format</h2>\
\
<p>The USB/IP protocol is documented in the Linux kernel. Key operation codes:</p>\
\
<table>\
  <tr><th>Op Code</th><th>Direction</th><th>Phase</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>OP_REQ_DEVLIST</code> (0x8005)</td><td>C\uc0\u8594 S</td><td>Discovery</td><td>Request list of exported devices</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>OP_REP_DEVLIST</code> (0x0005)</td><td>S\uc0\u8594 C</td><td>Discovery</td><td>Response with device descriptors</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>OP_REQ_IMPORT</code> (0x8003)</td><td>C\uc0\u8594 S</td><td>Discovery</td><td>Request to import (attach) a specific device</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>OP_REP_IMPORT</code> (0x0003)</td><td>S\uc0\u8594 C</td><td>Discovery</td><td>Response to import request (success/fail)</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>USBIP_CMD_SUBMIT</code> (0x00000001)</td><td>C\uc0\u8594 S</td><td>Transfer</td><td>Submit a URB to the device</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>USBIP_RET_SUBMIT</code> (0x00000003)</td><td>S\uc0\u8594 C</td><td>Transfer</td><td>Return the result of a submitted URB</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>USBIP_CMD_UNLINK</code> (0x00000002)</td><td>C\uc0\u8594 S</td><td>Transfer</td><td>Cancel (unlink) a previously submitted URB</td></tr>\
  <tr><td><code>USBIP_RET_UNLINK</code> (0x00000004)</td><td>S\uc0\u8594 C</td><td>Transfer</td><td>Response to unlink (ECONNRESET status)</td></tr>\
</table>\
\
<p>The protocol header uses big-endian byte order. Each <code>USBIP_CMD_SUBMIT</code> carries: command code, sequence number, device/bus IDs, direction, endpoint, URB transfer flags, buffer length, and the actual data payload. Isochronous packets also carry per-packet offsets and lengths.</p>\
\
