<!-- ========== VIDEO ========== -->\
<h2 id="video"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56567 </span> 14. USB Webcam/Video Streaming Over USB/IP \'97 Is It Possible?</h2>\
\
<div class="warn-box">\
  <strong>Short answer:</strong> Technically yes in limited scenarios. Practically, high-quality video over USB/IP is unreliable and not production-ready for most setups. Here's the full picture with no sugar-coating.\
</div>\
\
<p>According to the original USB/IP project, a remote USB webcam with an ov511 chip can be virtually attached to a computer. However, this was demonstrated on a Gigabit LAN under controlled conditions in 2005. Modern expectations \'97 1080p at 30fps, multiple cameras, compressed or uncompressed \'97 change the calculus dramatically.</p>\
\
<p>After binding and attaching a webcam via USB/IP, you should be able to use it as a normal device \'97 for example, <code>gst-launch v4l2src device=/dev/video0</code> \'97 but success depends heavily on the webcam's transfer type, resolution, compression format, and network conditions.</p>\
\
<h3>What Determines Success or Failure</h3>\
<div class="g3">\
  <div class="card cg">\
    <h4>\uc0\u9989  FAVORABLE conditions</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>Gigabit wired Ethernet (\uc0\u8804 1ms jitter)</li>\
      <li>Webcam supports MJPEG or H.264 compression</li>\
      <li>Low resolution (640\'d7480 or 320\'d7240)</li>\
      <li>Low frame rate (15fps or below)</li>\
      <li>Only one camera at a time</li>\
      <li>Running on a high-performance server-class CPU</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>\uc0\u10060  UNFAVORABLE conditions</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>WiFi (variable jitter, packet loss)</li>\
      <li>Uncompressed YUYV/NV12 format only</li>\
      <li>1080p or higher resolution</li>\
      <li>Multiple simultaneous cameras</li>\
      <li>Any WAN / Internet connection</li>\
      <li>The camera uses USB 3.0 SuperSpeed only</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cy">\
    <h4>\uc0\u9888 \u65039  MARGINAL \'97 depends on everything</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>MJPEG at 720p @ 30fps on Gigabit</li>\
      <li>USB audio at the same time as USB video</li>\
      <li>1Gbps switches with QoS prioritizing port 3240</li>\
      <li>Compressed webcams with USB 2.0 SuperSpeed fallback</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
</div>\
\
<h2 id="iso"><span class="ico">\uc0\u9201 \u65039 </span> 15. Isochronous Transfers \'97 The Root Cause of Video Problems</h2>\
\
<h3>The Bandwidth Math</h3>\
<div class="g2">\
  <div class="card">\
    <h4>YUYV Uncompressed (worst case)</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>320\'d7240 @ 30fps = ~3.3 MB/s raw</li>\
      <li>640\'d7480 @ 30fps = ~13 MB/s raw</li>\
      <li>1280\'d7720 @ 30fps = ~33 MB/s raw \uc0\u8592  <strong>already 44% of USB 2.0 isochronous budget</strong></li>\
      <li>1920\'d71080 @ 30fps = ~74 MB/s raw \uc0\u8592  <strong>exceeds entire USB 2.0 isochronous budget</strong></li>\
      <li>Add TCP overhead (+8\'9612%), USB/IP headers (+headers per URB), and kernel processing \uc0\u8594  numbers grow</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card">\
    <h4>MJPEG Compressed (better case)</h4>\
    <ul>\
      <li>320\'d7240 @ 30fps \uc0\u8776  0.5\'961 MB/s compressed</li>\
      <li>640\'d7480 @ 30fps \uc0\u8776  1\'963 MB/s compressed</li>\
      <li>1280\'d7720 @ 30fps \uc0\u8776  3\'968 MB/s compressed \u8592  <strong>viable on Gigabit LAN</strong></li>\
      <li>1920\'d71080 @ 30fps \uc0\u8776  8\'9620 MB/s compressed \u8592  <strong>marginal on Gigabit LAN</strong></li>\
      <li>Compression ratio depends on scene content \'97 fast-moving scenes need more bandwidth</li>\
    </ul>\
  </div>\
</div>\
\
<h3>Why TCP Jitter Kills Isochronous</h3>\
<p>USB isochronous transfers are scheduled in 1ms microframes (USB 2.0 HS) or 125\'b5s microframes (USB 3.x). The VHCI driver on the client must submit isochronous URBs at precise intervals matching this schedule. When a TCP packet arrives late (even by 2\'965ms, easily caused by a congested switch), the VHCI driver cannot queue the URB in time. The result is:</p>\
<ul>\
  <li><code>-EXDEV</code> or <code>-EINVAL</code> URB errors in kernel log</li>\
  <li>Corrupted video frames / green/black frames</li>\
  <li>V4L2 reporting broken pipe or device removed</li>\
  <li>Complete disconnection requiring manual re-attach</li>\
</ul>\
\
