  <tr><td>USB Scanners</td><td>Bulk</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>SANE (Scanner Access Now Easy) works over USB/IP without modification</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Keyboards</td><td>Interrupt</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>Small payloads; works on console and X11/Wayland</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Mice</td><td>Interrupt</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>Original paper demonstrated this; works over LAN with sub-5ms latency</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Gamepads / Joysticks</td><td>Interrupt</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Good</span></td><td>Very popular with Steam Deck / Linux gaming setups; sub-10ms typically</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Serial (FTDI, CH340, CP210x)</td><td>Bulk</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>Appears as /dev/ttyUSBx; perfect for remote microcontroller access</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Serial (CDC-ACM)</td><td>Bulk/Interrupt</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>Arduino, STM32, ESP32, etc.; appears as /dev/ttyACM0</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Security Dongles (HID)</td><td>HID/Control</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>License dongles; most common enterprise use case; works over VPN</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>Smartcard Readers</td><td>Control/Interrupt</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>PKI, CAC cards, authentication tokens</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Ethernet Adapters</td><td>Bulk</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Works</span></td><td>Unusual (networking over networking) but technically works</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB GPS Receivers</td><td>Bulk/Serial</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Good</span></td><td>Appears as serial port; NMEA data works fine over USB/IP</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Bluetooth Adapters</td><td>Bulk+Interrupt+Iso</td><td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Limited</span></td><td>Mixed transfer types; basic BT may work; high-bandwidth BT audio may not</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB WiFi Adapters</td><td>Bulk+Interrupt</td><td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Sometimes</span></td><td>Depends on driver and chipset; may work for basic networking</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Audio (Class 1, 44.1kHz)</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Usually works</span></td><td>Low bandwidth; most USB headsets and basic interfaces work on Gigabit LAN</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Audio (Class 2, \uc0\u8805 96kHz)</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="pmk">\u9888 \u65039  Variable</span></td><td>Higher sample rates; 24-bit 192kHz stereo \u8776  0.9MB/s; usually OK on Gigabit</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Audio (multi-channel)</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Variable</span></td><td>16+ channel interfaces (Focusrite Scarlett 18i20 etc.) need ~10MB/s; marginal</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Webcam (MJPEG, 640\'d7480)</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Sometimes</span></td><td>Low bandwidth; Gigabit LAN; try 320\'d7240 first</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Webcam (YUYV, 720p+)</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="xmk">\uc0\u10007  Usually fails</span></td><td>Too much bandwidth; TCP jitter fatal for isochronous scheduling</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Webcam (H.264 on-camera)</td><td>Bulk or Iso</td><td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Often works</span></td><td>Compressed on camera \u8594  much lower bandwidth; best chance for video</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Video Capture Cards</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="xmk">\uc0\u10007  Fails</span></td><td>Very high bandwidth; often proprietary protocols; don't try with USB/IP</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB TV Tuners</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="xmk">\uc0\u10007  Fails</span></td><td>High isochronous bandwidth; timing-critical; not viable over TCP</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB 3D Printers (serial)</td><td>Bulk/Serial</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Good</span></td><td>G-code via serial; works perfectly over USB/IP</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Drawing Tablets (Wacom etc.)</td><td>Interrupt/HID</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Good</span></td><td>HID protocol; works on LAN; latency may be noticeable for drawing</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Microscopes</td><td>Isochronous</td><td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Partial</span></td><td>Depends on compression; MJPEG models better than raw YUYV</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB NFC Readers</td><td>Interrupt/HID</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Good</span></td><td>Small payloads; works fine on LAN</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB UPS (APC, CyberPower)</td><td>HID</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  Excellent</span></td><td>Popular homelab use case \'97 monitor UPS from a VM/container via USB/IP</td></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB MIDI Controllers</td><td>Isochronous/Interrupt</td><td><span class="pmk">\uc0\u9888 \u65039  Variable</span></td><td>MIDI data itself is tiny; latency must be &lt;3ms for live playing; only on very fast LAN</td></tr>\
</table>\
\
<h2 id="fails"><span class="ico">\uc0\u10060 </span> 19. Hard Limits \'97 What USB/IP Cannot Do</h2>\
\
<div class="g2">\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>\uc0\u10060  No Native Encryption or Authentication</h4>\
    <p>USB/IP protocol has zero security mechanisms. Any machine that can reach TCP port 3240 can enumerate and attach your USB devices. This is a fundamental protocol design choice, not a bug. Must use SSH tunnel, WireGuard, or firewall rules.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>\uc0\u10060  No USB Power Delivery</h4>\
    <p>USB/IP forwards data only. A device that is powered by or charges via USB will not receive power through a USB/IP connection. If the device needs USB power to operate, it must be powered locally at the server side.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>\uc0\u10060  macOS Support \'97 Nearly Nonexistent</h4>\
    <p>There is no official USB/IP support for macOS. Experimental ports exist but are not production-ready as of 2026. macOS is essentially unsupported as either a USB/IP server or client natively.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>\uc0\u10060  USB 3.x SuperSpeed Over Real Networks</h4>\
    <p>USB 3.0 (5 Gbps), USB 3.1 (10 Gbps), and USB 3.2 (20 Gbps) devices' speeds are limited by the network itself. A 1 Gbps Ethernet connection can never saturate a USB 3.0 bus. USB/IP will always be the bottleneck.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>\uc0\u10060  Sub-Millisecond Timing</h4>\
    <p>Industrial USB devices needing microsecond-precise timing (certain DACs, high-precision motion controllers, some scientific instruments) cannot work reliably over any IP network due to inherent TCP jitter.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>\uc0\u10060  USB Gadget Mode / OTG Emulation</h4>\
    <p>USB/IP is for sharing real devices, not for making a computer emulate a USB device to another computer. USB gadget mode (<code>g_cdc</code>, <code>g_mass_storage</code>) is a separate Linux kernel feature. (Though VUDC \'97 Virtual USB Device Controller \'97 is an experimental USB/IP extension for this.)</p>\
  </div>\
</div>\
\
<h2 id="latency"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56522 </span> 20. LAN vs WiFi vs WAN Performance</h2>\
\
<table>\
  <tr><th>Device Type</th><th>Gigabit LAN</th><th>100Mbps LAN</th><th>WiFi 5GHz</th><th>WiFi 2.4GHz</th><th>VPN over Internet</th></tr>\
  <tr><td>USB Mass Storage</td><td><span class="chk">\uc0\u10003  ~100MB/s</span></td><td><span class="chk">\u10003  ~10MB/s</span></td><td><span class="chk">\u10003  ~30\'9680MB/s</span></td><td><span class="pmk">~ ~10\'9630MB/s</span></td><td><span class="chk">\u10003  ISP limited</span></td></tr>\
