\
<!-- ========== SECURITY ========== -->\
<h2 id="security"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56592 </span> 21. USB/IP Has Zero Native Security \'97 Full Threat Model</h2>\
\
<div class="danger-box">\
  <strong>\uc0\u9940  CRITICAL:</strong> USB/IP has no authentication, no encryption, and no access control in its protocol. Running USB/IP with port 3240 exposed to an untrusted network is a severe security risk. Anyone who can connect to that port can enumerate all exported devices and attach them \'97 potentially exfiltrating data from USB storage or cloning security tokens.\
</div>\
\
<h3>Threat Scenarios</h3>\
<div class="g2">\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>Attacker on local network</h4>\
    <p>Any device on the same LAN can connect to port 3240 without credentials, see all exported devices, and attach them. For shared networks (corporate WiFi, shared housing), this is a real risk.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>Man-in-the-middle</h4>\
    <p>USB/IP traffic is unencrypted plaintext. An attacker who can intercept traffic (ARP poisoning, compromised switch) can read all data sent to/from the USB device, including storage files, keystrokes from HID devices, and authentication tokens.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>Exposed to the Internet</h4>\
    <p>If port 3240 is forwarded through a router to the Internet, any scanning bot worldwide can discover and interact with your USB devices. This must never be done without a VPN wrapper.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card cr">\
    <h4>usbipd-win firewall rule scope</h4>\
    <p>The installer creates a firewall rule called <code>usbipd</code> allowing all local subnets to connect to the service. You can modify this firewall rule to fine-tune access control. Narrow this to specific IP addresses in production environments.</p>\
  </div>\
</div>\
\
<h2 id="ssh-tunnel"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56594 </span> 22. SSH Tunnel Method \'97 Step by Step</h2>\
\
<p>SSH tunneling is the simplest way to add encryption and authentication to USB/IP over an untrusted network. You can set up a reverse tunnel by SSH from Windows to Linux \'97 using <code>ssh.exe user@&lt;IP-address-of-Linux-reachable-from-Windows&gt; -R &lt;IP-address-of-Linux&gt;:127.0.0.1:3240</code> \'97 which allows the Linux machine to reach the Windows USB/IP server as if it were local.</p>\
\
<h3>Forward Tunnel (Linux client \uc0\u8594  Linux server over SSH)</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># On the CLIENT \'97 forward remote port 3240 to local 3240</span>\
ssh -L 3240:localhost:3240 user@usb-server.example.com -N &amp;\
\
<span class="cm"># Then attach as if the server were local</span>\
sudo usbip attach -r 127.0.0.1 -b 1-1.5\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Reverse Tunnel (Windows server \uc0\u8594  Linux client)</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># On the WINDOWS machine \'97 forward local port 3240 back through SSH to Linux</span>\
ssh.exe user@linux-client.example.com -R 127.0.0.1:3240:127.0.0.1:3240 -N\
\
<span class="cm"># On the Linux client \'97 now attach via 127.0.0.1</span>\
sudo usbip attach -r 127.0.0.1 -b 1-1\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Making the SSH Tunnel Persistent with systemd</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># /etc/systemd/system/usbip-ssh-tunnel.service</span>\
[Unit]\
Description=SSH tunnel for USB/IP\
After=network-online.target\
Wants=network-online.target\
\
[Service]\
User=usbipuser\
ExecStart=/usr/bin/ssh -NL 3240:localhost:3240 \\\
  -o ServerAliveInterval=30 \\\
  -o ServerAliveCountMax=3 \\\
  -o ExitOnForwardFailure=yes \\\
  -i /home/usbipuser/.ssh/usbip_key \\\
  user@usb-server.example.com\
Restart=on-failure\
RestartSec=10\
\
[Install]\
WantedBy=multi-user.target\
</pre>\
\
<h2 id="wireguard"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u57057 \u65039 </span> 23. WireGuard VPN \'97 Best Practice for USB/IP Over WAN</h2>\
\
<p>WireGuard is a communication protocol and free and open-source software that implements encrypted virtual private networks. It aims to be lighter and better performing than IPsec and OpenVPN. The WireGuard protocol passes traffic over UDP. In March 2020, the Linux version reached a stable production release and was incorporated into the Linux 5.6 kernel.</p>\
\
<p>WireGuard is compatible with Windows, macOS, Android, and iOS in addition to Linux. Its lean codebase of around 4,000 lines, compared to tens of thousands in other VPN protocols, makes security auditing far simpler. It uses public key cryptography for authentication, eliminating the need for traditional certificate authorities.</p>\
\
<div class="ok-box">\
  <strong>WireGuard is the recommended tunnel for USB/IP over any untrusted network.</strong> Once both machines are on the same WireGuard VPN, USB/IP traffic flows over the encrypted WireGuard interface. You connect to the WireGuard IP address of the server instead of its public IP. No firewall exposure of port 3240 needed.\
</div>\
\
<p>Note: WireGuard explicitly does not support tunneling over TCP, due to the classically terrible network performance of tunneling TCP-over-TCP. Rather, transforming WireGuard's UDP packets into TCP is the job of an upper layer of obfuscation, and can be accomplished by projects like udptunnel and udp2raw. For USB/IP (which is already TCP), this is fine \'97 USB/IP's TCP runs inside WireGuard's UDP, not the other way around.</p>\
\
<h2 id="firewall"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55358 \u56817 </span> 24. Firewall Rules and Access Control</h2>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Linux \'97 allow only specific host to connect to USB/IP</span>\
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 3240 -s 192.168.1.50 -j ACCEPT\
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 3240 -j DROP\
\
<span class="cm"># Or with nftables:</span>\
nft add rule inet filter input ip saddr 192.168.1.50 tcp dport 3240 accept\
nft add rule inet filter input tcp dport 3240 drop\
\
<span class="cm"># ufw (Ubuntu/Debian):</span>\
ufw allow from 192.168.1.50 to any port 3240\
\
<span class="cm"># Windows PowerShell \'97 narrow the usbipd firewall rule to a specific IP:</span>\
Set-NetFirewallRule -Name "usbipd" -RemoteAddress 192.168.1.50\
</pre>\
\
<!-- ========== AUTO-CONNECT ========== -->\
<h2 id="auto-linux"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56577 </span> 25. Linux Auto-Connect \'97 systemd, udev, Vendor ID</h2>\
\
<h3>Method 1: systemd Template Service (bind by bus ID)</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># /etc/systemd/system/usbip-bind@.service</span>\
[Unit]\
Description=USB-IP Binding on bus id %I\
After=network-online.target usbipd.service\
Wants=network-online.target\
Requires=usbipd.service\
\
[Service]\
Type=simple\
ExecStart=/usr/bin/usbip bind -b %i\
RemainAfterExit=yes\
ExecStop=/usr/bin/usbip unbind -b %i\
Restart=on-failure\
\
[Install]\
WantedBy=multi-user.target\
\
<span class="cm"># Enable for device at bus ID 1-1.5:</span>\
systemctl enable --now usbip-bind@1-1.5.service\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Method 2: Bind by Vendor:Product ID (more stable \'97 bus IDs can change)</h3>\
<p>If bus IDs are inconsistent and dynamically assigned at each system boot, binding by vendor/device ID can be used alternatively. The usbip-systemd AUR package supports config files in <code>/etc/usbip/bind-devices/</code>:</p>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># /etc/systemd/system/usbip-bind-id@.service</span>\
[Unit]\
Description=USB-IP Binding device id %I\
After=network-online.target usbipd.service\
Wants=network-online.target\
Requires=usbipd.service\
\
[Service]\
Type=simple\
ExecStart=/bin/sh -c "/usr/sbin/usbip bind \\\
  --$(/usr/sbin/usbip list -p -l | grep '#usbid=%i#' | cut '-d#' -f1)"\
RemainAfterExit=yes\
ExecStop=/bin/sh -c "/usr/sbin/usbip unbind \\\
  --$(/usr/sbin/usbip list -p -l | grep '#usbid=%i#' | cut '-d#' -f1)"\
Restart=on-failure\
\
[Install]\
WantedBy=multi-user.target\
\
<span class="cm"># Enable for Logitech Unifying Receiver (046d:c52b):</span>\
systemctl enable --now usbip-bind-id@046d:c52b.service\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Method 3: Client Auto-Attach via systemd</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># /etc/systemd/system/usbip-attach@.service</span>\
[Unit]\
Description=USB-IP Client Attach %I\
After=network-online.target\
Wants=network-online.target\
\
[Service]\
Type=oneshot\
<span class="cm"># Format: server_ip/bus_id</span>\
ExecStart=/usr/bin/usbip attach \\\
  -r %I \\\
  -b $(/usr/bin/usbip list -p -r %I | grep '#usbid=046d:c52b#' | cut '-d#' -f1)\
RemainAfterExit=yes\
\
[Install]\
WantedBy=multi-user.target\
\
systemctl enable --now usbip-attach@192.168.1.100.service\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Method 4: udev Rules for Server-Side Hotplug Auto-Bind</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># /etc/udev/rules.d/90-usbip-autobind.rules</span>\
<span class="cm"># Auto-bind Logitech Unifying Receiver when plugged in</span>\
ACTION=="add", SUBSYSTEM=="usb", \\\
  ATTRS\{idVendor\}=="046d", ATTRS\{idProduct\}=="c52b", \\\
  RUN+="/usr/bin/usbip bind -b $attr\{busnum\}-$attr\{devpath\}"\
\
<span class="cm"># Auto-unbind on removal</span>\
ACTION=="remove", SUBSYSTEM=="usb", \\\
  ATTRS\{idVendor\}=="046d", ATTRS\{idProduct\}=="c52b", \\\
  RUN+="/usr/bin/usbip unbind -b $attr\{busnum\}-$attr\{devpath\}"\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Method 5: usbip-systemd (AUR) \'97 Simplest Config-Based Approach</h3>\
<p>usbip-systemdAUR provides systemd service files for binding by vendor/device id and for connecting by hostname and vendor/device id. For each device create a <code>device.conf</code> in <code>/etc/usbip/bind-devices/</code> with <code>USBIP_DEVICE</code> set to the vendor/product id. For each host/device create a <code>device.conf</code> in <code>/etc/usbip/remote-devices/</code> with <code>HOST</code> set and <code>USBIP_DEVICE</code> set to the vendor/product id.</p>\
\
<h2 id="auto-windows"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56577 </span> 26. Windows Auto-Connect \'97 usbipd-win, Task Scheduler, wsl-usb-manager</h2>\
\
<h3>usbipd-win --auto-attach (simplest)</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Bind the device (persistent, survives reboots):</span>\
usbipd bind --busid 1-1\
\
<span class="cm"># Attach to WSL with auto-reattach on unplug:</span>\
usbipd attach --wsl --busid 1-1 --auto-attach\
\
<span class="cm"># Attach to a specific WSL distribution:</span>\
usbipd attach --wsl Ubuntu-22.04 --busid 1-1 --auto-attach\
</pre>\
\
<div class="warn-box">\
  <strong>Caveat:</strong> <code>--auto-attach</code> re-attaches after device unplug/replug but does <strong>not</strong> survive a full Windows reboot. Use Task Scheduler or wsl-usb-manager profiles for boot persistence.\
</div>\
\
<h3>Task Scheduler for Boot Persistence</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># PowerShell \'97 create scheduled task that runs at system startup</span>\
$action = New-ScheduledTaskAction `\
  -Execute "usbipd" `\
  -Argument "attach --wsl --busid 1-1"\
$trigger = New-ScheduledTaskTrigger -AtStartup\
$principal = New-ScheduledTaskPrincipal `\
  -UserId "SYSTEM" `\
  -LogonType ServiceAccount `\
  -RunLevel Highest\
$settings = New-ScheduledTaskSettingsSet `\
  -ExecutionTimeLimit (New-TimeSpan -Minutes 5)\
Register-ScheduledTask `\
  -TaskName "USB-IP Auto-Attach WSL" `\
  -Action $action `\
  -Trigger $trigger `\
  -Principal $principal `\
  -Settings $settings\
</pre>\
\
<h3>nickbeth/wsl-usb-manager \'97 GUI Profiles (Easiest)</h3>\
<p>Open wsl-usb-manager \uc0\u8594  select device \u8594  click "Persist" or "Auto-attach" \u8594  device re-attaches after every unplug and every boot automatically. No scripting required.</p>\
\
<h2 id="auto-hotplug"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56588 </span> 27. Hotplug \'97 Reconnect After Unplug Without Manual Steps</h2>\
\
<p>The USBip project implements hot plugging for USB devices over TCP/IP on Linux. It creates a systemctl service on both the client and the server that binds all available devices. When a device that is bound and attached remotely is unplugged, the device is automatically detached on the client and unbound on the host. After that the state is the same as if it was never bound or attached.</p>\
\
<p>For per-device hotplug on the server side, combine udev rules (Section 25, Method 4) with systemd services. On the client side, write a script that polls and re-attaches:</p>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm">#!/bin/bash</span>\
<span class="cm"># /usr/local/bin/usbip-watchdog.sh</span>\
<span class="cm"># Continuously monitor and re-attach a device</span>\
\
SERVER="192.168.1.100"\
VENDOR_ID="046d:c52b"\
\
while true; do\
  if ! usbip port | grep -q "$VENDOR_ID"; then\
    echo "Device not attached, attempting to attach..."\
    BUS_ID=$(usbip list -p -r $SERVER | grep "#usbid=$VENDOR_ID#" \\\
      | cut '-d#' -f1 | sed 's/busid=//')\
    if [ -n "$BUS_ID" ]; then\
      sudo usbip attach -r $SERVER -b "$BUS_ID"\
    fi\
  fi\
  sleep 5\
done\
</pre>\
\
<!-- ========== PLATFORM GUIDES ========== -->\
<h2 id="guide-linux"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56359 </span> 28. Full Linux Setup Guide (Server + Client)</h2>\
\
<h3>Server Setup</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># 1. Install usbip tools (Debian/Ubuntu)</span>\
sudo apt install usbip linux-tools-generic\
\
<span class="cm"># 2. Load kernel modules</span>\
sudo modprobe usbip_core\
sudo modprobe usbip_host\
\
<span class="cm"># 3. Make modules persistent</span>\
echo "usbip_core" | sudo tee -a /etc/modules\
echo "usbip_host" | sudo tee -a /etc/modules\
\
<span class="cm"># 4. Start the daemon</span>\
sudo usbipd -D\
\
<span class="cm"># Or as a systemd service:</span>\
sudo systemctl enable --now usbipd.service\
\
<span class="cm"># 5. List local devices</span>\
sudo usbip list -l\
\
<span class="cm"># 6. Bind a device (replace 1-1.5 with your bus ID)</span>\
sudo usbip bind -b 1-1.5\
\
<span class="cm"># 7. Verify it's exported</span>\
sudo usbip list -r 127.0.0.1\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Client Setup</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># 1. Install usbip tools</span>\
sudo apt install usbip\
\
<span class="cm"># 2. Load VHCI driver</span>\
sudo modprobe vhci-hcd\
\
<span class="cm"># Make persistent:</span>\
echo "vhci-hcd" | sudo tee -a /etc/modules\
\
<span class="cm"># 3. List devices on remote server</span>\
sudo usbip list -r 192.168.1.100\
\
<span class="cm"># 4. Attach the device</span>\
sudo usbip attach -r 192.168.1.100 -b 1-1.5\
\
<span class="cm"># 5. Verify attachment</span>\
usbip port\
lsusb\
\
<span class="cm"># 6. Detach when done</span>\
sudo usbip detach -p 0\
</pre>\
\
<h2 id="guide-windows"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55358 \u56991 </span> 29. Full Windows + WSL Setup Guide</h2>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Step 1: Install usbipd-win (requires Windows 10 2004+)</span>\
winget install --interactive --exact dorsel.usbipd-win\
\
<span class="cm"># Step 2: Update WSL kernel (important for device driver support)</span>\
wsl --update\
\
<span class="cm"># Step 3: List USB devices (run PowerShell as Admin)</span>\
usbipd list\
\
<span class="cm"># Step 4: Bind the device you want to share</span>\
usbipd bind --busid 1-1\
<span class="cm"># Note: binding is persistent across reboots</span>\
\
<span class="cm"># Step 5: Attach to WSL</span>\
usbipd attach --wsl --busid 1-1\
\
<span class="cm"># Step 6: In WSL, verify the device appears</span>\
lsusb\
ls /dev/ttyUSB* /dev/ttyACM* /dev/sd*\
\
<span class="cm"># Step 7: When done, detach</span>\
usbipd detach --busid 1-1\
</pre>\
\
<h2 id="guide-pi"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55356 \u57171 </span> 30. Raspberry Pi as USB/IP Server</h2>\
\
<p>The Raspberry Pi is an extremely popular USB/IP server platform \'97 it's low-power, inexpensive, always-on, and has multiple USB ports. Pair it with a USB hub and you have a dedicated multi-device USB sharing appliance for under $50.</p>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Raspberry Pi OS (Debian-based) \'97 full setup</span>\
sudo apt update && sudo apt install usbip\
\
<span class="cm"># The Pi kernel already includes usbip modules</span>\
sudo modprobe usbip_core usbip_host\
\
<span class="cm"># Make persistent</span>\
echo -e "usbip_core\\nusbip_host" | sudo tee -a /etc/modules\
\
<span class="cm"># Start daemon and enable at boot</span>\
sudo systemctl enable --now usbipd.service\
\
<span class="cm"># Bind all USB devices at once (useful for a Pi USB hub):</span>\
for busid in $(usbip list -l | grep 'busid' | awk '\{print $3\}'); do\
  sudo usbip bind -b $busid 2>/dev/null\
done\
</pre>\
\
<div class="card ca">\
  <h4>Raspberry Pi USB/IP Hardware Setup Tips</h4>\
  <ul>\
    <li>Use a <strong>powered USB hub</strong> \'97 Pi's USB port power is limited; powered hubs prevent device drop-outs</li>\
    <li>Use <strong>Gigabit Ethernet</strong> (Pi 4+ has true GbE) \'97 avoids WiFi jitter</li>\
    <li>Set a <strong>static IP</strong> for the Pi so clients always connect to the same address</li>\
    <li>Disable WiFi if using Ethernet: <code>sudo rfkill block wifi</code></li>\
    <li>Use a <strong>good power supply</strong> (5V/3A minimum for Pi 4) \'97 USB device power draw can cause instability on undersized supplies</li>\
    <li>Consider adding a small SSD as a boot drive instead of SD card for reliability</li>\
  </ul>\
</div>\
\
<h2 id="guide-openwrt"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56545 </span> 31. OpenWrt Router as USB/IP Server</h2>\
\
<p>OpenWrt can be configured as a USB over IP server, allowing you to access USB devices connected to your router from any computer on your network \'97 connecting storage drives, printers, and other USB peripherals without needing to plug them directly into your machine.</p>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Install USB/IP packages on OpenWrt</span>\
opkg update\
opkg install usbip usbip-client usbip-server kmod-usbip kmod-usbip-host\
\
<span class="cm"># Load modules</span>\
modprobe usbip_core\
modprobe usbip_host\
\
<span class="cm"># Start server</span>\
usbipd -D\
\
<span class="cm"># List and bind devices</span>\
usbip list -l\
usbip bind -b 1-1\
\
<span class="cm"># Make persistent via /etc/rc.local or a startup script</span>\
</pre>\
\
<div class="warn-box">\
  <strong>OpenWrt Limitations:</strong> Not all OpenWrt-compatible routers have USB ports. Check your router's hardware spec. USB 2.0 is common; USB 3.0 is less so. CPU performance on routers is much lower than a Pi \'97 avoid high-bandwidth devices (video, audio). Best for: USB storage, USB-to-serial adapters, USB printers on the network.\
</div>\
\
<h2 id="guide-proxmox"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56741 \u65039 </span> 32. Proxmox: USB Passthrough to VMs and LXC Containers</h2>\
\
<h3>Option A: USB/IP Client Inside a VM (via QEMU)</h3>\
<p>QEMU can act as a USB/IP client natively, connecting to any USB/IP server and presenting the device inside the VM. Oracle VM VirtualBox supports passing through USB devices which are exposed over the network using the USB over IP protocol without the need to configure the client side provided by the kernel and usbip tools. Furthermore, this feature works with VirtualBox running on any supported host, rather than just Linux alone. To enable support: <code>VBoxManage usbdevsource add unique-name --backend USB-IP --address device-server[:port]</code>. USB devices exported on the device server are then accessible through the GUI or VBoxManage like any USB devices attached locally.</p>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># QEMU command-line: add USB/IP device from remote server</span>\
-device usb-host,hostbus=1,hostaddr=2 \\\
-usb \\\
-device nec-usb-xhci,id=xhci\
<span class="cm"># Or via qemu-system USB passthrough:</span>\
qemu-system-x86_64 \\\
  -device usb-host,id=usb0,vendorid=0x046d,productid=0xc52b\
</pre>\
\
<h3>Option B: Direct LXC USB Device Passthrough (simpler for static devices)</h3>\
<p>For devices physically attached to the Proxmox host, the direct LXC bind-mount approach is simpler than USB/IP:</p>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Find your device's major:minor numbers</span>\
lsusb\
ls -l /dev/bus/usb/004/005\
<span class="cm"># e.g., shows: crw-rw-r-- 1 root root 189, 388 ...</span>\
\
<span class="cm"># Edit LXC config: /etc/pve/lxc/&lt;CTID&gt;.conf</span>\
<span class="cm"># Add (Proxmox 8.1+ \'97 preferred method):</span>\
pct set &lt;CTID&gt; --dev0 /dev/bus/usb/004/005\
\
<span class="cm"># OR manually add to .conf:</span>\
lxc.cgroup2.devices.allow: c 189:388 rwm\
lxc.mount.entry: /dev/bus/usb/004/005 dev/bus/usb/004/005 none bind,optional,create=file\
\
<span class="cm"># For serial devices (ttyACM0):</span>\
lxc.cgroup2.devices.allow: c 166:* rwm\
lxc.mount.entry: /dev/ttyACM0 dev/ttyACM0 none bind,optional,create=file\
</pre>\
\
<div class="warn-box">\
  <strong>Bus ID instability:</strong> The bus ID in <code>/dev/bus/usb/X/Y</code> changes when devices are plugged/unplugged or on reboot. Use a udev rule to ensure stable device paths, using <code>pct set</code> as the official way to change the LXC configuration \'97 this handles cluster setups correctly and will restart the container if needed.\
</div>\
\
<h2 id="guide-docker"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56331 </span> 33. Docker and Container USB Passthrough</h2>\
\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Method 1: Pass entire USB bus (broad access)</span>\
docker run --privileged \\\
  -v /dev/bus/usb:/dev/bus/usb \\\
  my-container\
\
<span class="cm"># Method 2: Pass specific device (safer)</span>\
docker run \\\
  --device /dev/bus/usb/001/003:/dev/bus/usb/001/003 \\\
  my-container\
\
<span class="cm"># Method 3: Pass serial device</span>\
docker run \\\
  --device /dev/ttyUSB0:/dev/ttyUSB0 \\\
  --group-add dialout \\\
  my-container\
\
<span class="cm"># Method 4: udev rule to create a stable symlink for Docker</span>\
<span class="cm"># /etc/udev/rules.d/99-mydevice.rules:</span>\
SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ATTRS\{idVendor\}=="046d", ATTRS\{idProduct\}=="c52b", \\\
  SYMLINK+="my-device", MODE="0666"\
\
<span class="cm"># Then use the symlink in Docker:</span>\
docker run --device /dev/my-device:/dev/my-device my-container\
</pre>\
\
<h2 id="guide-qemu"><span class="ico">\uc0\u9889 </span> 34. QEMU/KVM and VirtualBox USB/IP Client</h2>\
\
<h3>QEMU Native USB/IP Client</h3>\
<pre>\
<span class="cm"># Add a USB/IP device to a QEMU VM</span>\
<span class="cm"># In the QEMU command line or via virsh XML:</span>\
\
<span class="cm"># List available devices on remote server (from host):</span>\
usbip list -r 192.168.1.100\
\
<span class="cm"># virsh XML snippet for USB/IP passthrough:</span>\
&lt;hostdev mode='subsystem' type='usb'&gt;\
  &lt;source&gt;\
    &lt;address type='usb-serial' bus='1' device='3'/&gt;\
  &lt;/source&gt;\
&lt;/hostdev&gt;\
</pre>\
\
<h3>VirtualBox Native USB/IP</h3>\
<p>To enable USB/IP passthrough in VirtualBox, use: <code>VBoxManage usbdevsource add unique-name --backend USB-IP --address device-server[:port]</code>. This can be used multiple times to access different device servers. USB devices exported on the device server are then accessible through the VirtualBox GUI or VBoxManage, like any USB devices attached locally.</p>\
\
<h2 id="guide-macos"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55356 \u57166 </span> 35. macOS \'97 The Platform USB/IP Forgot</h2>\
\
<div class="danger-box">\
  <strong>macOS has no official USB/IP support.</strong> There is no Apple-provided or community-maintained stable USB/IP client or server for macOS. The original project acknowledged this gap but never filled it.\
</div>\
\
<p>Options available as of 2026:</p>\
<ul>\
  <li><strong>VirtualHere</strong> \'97 commercial tool; macOS client and server both work well; best option for macOS USB/IP equivalence</li>\
  <li><strong>FlexiHub</strong> \'97 commercial; full macOS support; uses its own protocol</li>\
  <li><strong>USB Network Gate</strong> \'97 commercial; macOS client available</li>\
  <li><strong>VirtualBox on macOS</strong> \'97 can use VirtualBox's built-in USB/IP client to connect to Linux servers; runs inside the VM, not native macOS</li>\
  <li><strong>Experimental usbip-macOS forks</strong> \'97 exist on GitHub but untested/unmaintained; not recommended for production</li>\
</ul>\
\
