<!-- ========== DECISION ========== -->\
<h2 id="decision"><span class="ico">\uc0\u55357 \u56826 \u65039 </span> 44. Decision Tree \'97 Which Tool for Which Situation</h2>\
\
<div class="g2">\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55357 \u56359  Linux server \u8594  Linux client, same LAN</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  <strong>Linux kernel usbip</strong> directly. Load <code>usbip_host</code> server-side, <code>vhci-hcd</code> client-side. Systemd for auto-connect. GUI: K-Francis-H/usbip-gui or alunux/usbip-service-discovery.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55358 \u56991  Windows \u8594  WSL2 (simplest path)</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  Install <strong>dorssel/usbipd-win</strong> first. Use <strong>nickbeth/wsl-usb-manager</strong> GUI for everything including auto-attach profiles.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55358 \u56991  Windows server \u8594  remote Linux client (Proxmox, VM, etc.)</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  <strong>dorssel/usbipd-win</strong> on Windows + standard Linux usbip client on the other side. Or: QEMU native USB/IP client in your VM config.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55356 \u57171  Always-on USB device sharing (headless)</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  <strong>Raspberry Pi</strong> with Linux usbip + systemd services. ~$50 total. Pairs with any USB/IP client on Linux, Windows (via usbipd-win client), or VirtualBox.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55357 \u56592  Need it to work over the Internet securely</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  Set up <strong>WireGuard</strong> or <strong>Tailscale</strong> between machines first. Then USB/IP as if on a LAN. Never expose port 3240 raw to the Internet.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55357 \u56508  Need it to "just work" without configuration headache</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  <strong>VirtualHere</strong> (1 device free, all platforms) or <strong>FlexiHub</strong> (subscription). Better isochronous handling, simpler setup, auto-connect out of the box.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55357 \u56567  Need webcam sharing specifically</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  Do NOT use raw USB/IP for HD video. Instead: <strong>GStreamer</strong> or <strong>MediaMTX</strong> for RTSP streaming. If you specifically need it to appear as a local USB webcam on the remote machine, try <strong>VirtualHere</strong> at MJPEG low-res, or use <strong>v4l2loopback</strong> to inject an RTSP stream as a virtual camera.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55356 \u57255  Need audio interface / USB audio sharing</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  Try USB/IP on Gigabit LAN first (USB Audio Class 1 usually works). If it doesn't, use <strong>PipeWire network streaming</strong> (Linux) or <strong>Snapcast</strong> (all platforms) or <strong>VirtualHere</strong>.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55356 \u57262  Linux gaming \'97 gamepad + audio from headless PC</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  <strong>seastwood/usb-audio-ip-client</strong> \'97 designed exactly for this use case with PipeWire integration.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55356 \u57312  Home Assistant Zigbee/Z-Wave dongle over USB/IP</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  <strong>cryptedx/ha-usbip-client</strong> add-on \'97 auto-connects at HA startup; perfect for running HA in a container while the dongle is on a remote Pi.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u55357 \u56741 \u65039  Proxmox VM needs USB device</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  Option A (device physically on Proxmox host): direct LXC bind-mount with <code>pct set --dev0</code> (PVE 8.1+). Option B (device on remote machine): set up USB/IP on remote, use QEMU's native USB/IP client in the VM config.</p>\
  </div>\
  <div class="card ca">\
    <h4>\uc0\u9000 \u65039  Just need keyboard + mouse shared (not USB devices)</h4>\
    <p>\uc0\u8594  <strong>Deskflow</strong> \'97 this is not a USB/IP problem at all. Deskflow/Input Leap/Lan Mouse handle this perfectly without any USB/IP stack.</p>\
  </div>\
</div>\
\
<hr class="divider">\
\
<div class="summary-big">\
  <h3 style="color:#a78bfa;margin-bottom:16px">The Complete Picture in One Place</h3>\
  <p><strong>USB/IP is a mature, Linux-kernel-native protocol</strong> that transparently tunnels USB device communications over TCP/IP. It has been in the Linux mainline kernel since 2014 and has spawned a rich ecosystem. It is <em>excellent</em> for: mass storage, HID devices, serial adapters, security dongles, printers, smartcard readers, UPS monitors, and USB audio on Gigabit LAN. It <em>struggles</em> with: high-bandwidth isochronous video, WiFi, WAN connections, USB 3.x speeds, and devices needing sub-millisecond timing. It has <em>zero native security</em> \'97 always use WireGuard/Tailscale or SSH tunneling when crossing untrusted networks.</p>\
  <p style="margin-top:12px">On <strong>Windows</strong>: install <code>dorssel/usbipd-win</code> (server/backbone), optionally <code>vadimgrn/usbip-win2</code> (client driver), and <code>nickbeth/wsl-usb-manager</code> (GUI with auto-attach). On <strong>Linux</strong>: use the kernel modules directly + systemd services + udev rules. On <strong>Raspberry Pi</strong>: the cheapest dedicated USB/IP server you can build. On <strong>macOS</strong>: use VirtualHere or FlexiHub. For <strong>video</strong>: use GStreamer or MediaMTX instead of USB/IP. For <strong>enterprise</strong>: VirtualHere or FlexiHub. For <strong>auto-connect-everything</strong>: combine usbipd-win's <code>--auto-attach</code> with wsl-usb-manager profiles on Windows, or systemd + udev on Linux \'97 fully automated, zero manual steps after initial setup.</p>\
</div>\
